      <hedline>
        <hl1>Lieberman and Choice</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Deborah E Lipstadt letter says Sen Joseph Lieberman's pro-choice stance on abortion is only position that traditional Jew could take</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In ''Bound by Belief'' (Op-Ed, Aug. 15), Martin E. Marty notes that Senator Joseph I. Lieberman's ''commitment to help keep abortion legal angers those conservative Protestants who think orthodoxy must mean anti-abortion.''</p>
        <p>Yet Senator Lieberman's support of Roe v. Wade is the only position that a traditional Jew could take. Pro-choice means that the government does not decree what should be done.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In ''Bound by Belief'' (Op-Ed, Aug. 15), Martin E. Marty notes that Senator Joseph I. Lieberman's ''commitment to help keep abortion legal angers those conservative Protestants who think orthodoxy must mean anti-abortion.''</p>
        <p>Yet Senator Lieberman's support of Roe v. Wade is the only position that a traditional Jew could take. Pro-choice means that the government does not decree what should be done.</p>
        <p>Jewish law mandates abortion in certain cases, like saving the life of the mother. The precise application of this depends on the particulars of the case.</p>
        <p>Outlawing abortion would prevent rabbis from fulfilling their function as interpreters of Jewish law.</p>
        <p>DEBORAH E. LIPSTADT  Atlanta, Aug. 18, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is the director of the Institute for Jewish Studies, Emory University.</p>
      </block>
